Real-World Git & GitHub Workflow Simulation
Step 1: Understanding the real-life scenario
Imagine you are working as a junior developer in a small software team. The company is building a simple website project. Multiple developers are working on the same codebase, so they use Git and GitHub to manage changes safely.

Your task is to simulate this professional workflow on your own computer. You will practise creating a repository, making commits, working with branches, pushing code to GitHub, and resolving conflicts just like in a real company environment.

This assignment exists to teach you how real development teams avoid losing code, track progress, and collaborate efficiently.

Step 2: Creating and managing a local Git repository
Create a new project folder named module-6-git-workflow. Inside the folder, create a simple file called index.html and write a basic HTML structure with a heading that says “Git Practice Project”.

Open the folder in VS Code and initialize Git using the appropriate command. After initializing, check the repository status and observe which files are untracked.

Stage the file properly and commit it with a meaningful commit message describing what you added. View the commit history to confirm that the commit was saved correctly.

Step 3: Working with branches like a professional developer
Create a new branch named feature-section. Switch to this branch and edit the index.html file by adding a new section under the heading. For example, add a paragraph describing a new feature of the website.

After making changes, check the status, stage the file, and commit it with a message explaining what feature you added.

Now switch back to the main branch and notice that the new section does not appear there yet.

Merge the feature-section branch into the main branch and confirm that the changes are now combined.

Step 4: Connecting the project with GitHub
Create a GitHub account if you do not already have one. On GitHub, create a new empty repository.

Connect your local repository to the remote GitHub repository using the proper remote command.

Push your local commits to GitHub and verify by refreshing the repository page in the browser.

Step 5: Simulating collaboration using changes
Modify the index.html file again locally by adding another paragraph.

Commit the changes and push them to GitHub.

Then, using GitHub’s interface or GitHub Desktop, create a new branch and modify the same file in a slightly different way.

Fetch the remote changes back to your local machine and try merging them.

If a merge conflict occurs, carefully open the file, review both versions of code, fix the conflict manually, and commit the resolved version.

This step teaches you how real developers handle code conflicts calmly instead of panicking.

Step 6: Using Pull Requests for review
On GitHub, create a Pull Request from your new branch to the main branch.

Write a short description explaining what changes you made.

Merge the Pull Request after reviewing it.

This simulates how teams review code before adding it to production.

Step 7: Reviewing history and workflow
View the commit history locally and on GitHub.

Observe how each commit tells a story of what was changed and when.

Open a file’s modification history on GitHub and understand how tracking works.

Step 8: Final review and submission
Make sure your repository includes:

• Multiple commits

• At least one branch created and merged

• Code pushed to GitHub

• A Pull Request created and merged

• A merge conflict resolved

For submission, please provide: The public repository link.